---
import BaseLayout from '@layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Banner from '@components/Banner.astro';
import SectionHead from '@components/SectionHead.astro';
import SectionBlurb from '@components/SectionBlurb.astro';

// Cosmos map — inlined for now. Phase 4 will vendor planets.json into claw-planet
// and read from manifest; until then this is hardcoded with the same fields.
// Source of truth: aguidetocloud-revamp/data/planets.toml.
const cosmosMap = [
  { slug: 'earth',    name: 'A Guide to Cloud', url: 'https://www.aguidetocloud.com/',         tagline: 'free cloud + AI guides for IT pros — tools, certs, blog, videos' },
  { slug: 'guided',   name: 'Guided',            url: 'https://www.aguidetocloud.com/guided/', tagline: 'practice exams that don\'t gatekeep — $9, not $79' },
  { slug: 'brainbar', name: 'CMD',               url: 'https://cmd.aguidetocloud.com/',         tagline: 'Microsoft jargon AND error code decoder' },
  { slug: 'shift',    name: 'Shift',             url: 'https://shift.aguidetocloud.com/',       tagline: 'how AI is changing real jobs, role by role' },
  { slug: 'plainai',  name: 'Plain AI',          url: 'https://plainai.aguidetocloud.com/',     tagline: 'AI explained plainly, for everyone' },
  { slug: 'agentic',  name: 'Agentic',           url: 'https://agents.aguidetocloud.com/',      tagline: 'MCP reviews, recipes, vendor takes — for techies building with agents' },
  { slug: 'claw',     name: 'Claw',              url: 'https://claw.aguidetocloud.com/',         tagline: 'field notebook for AI tooling — Claude Code, Codex, Gemini, Copilot Studio + ATK, OpenClaw (you are here)', here: true },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About — Claw"
  description="A practitioner's field notebook for AI tools you can run, wire, script, compare, or operationally reason about. Why this exists, who's behind it, the verification-states legend, the scope guardrails."
  ogImage="/og/home.png"
>
  <Banner />

  <SectionHead num="0.1" title="What this is" />
  <SectionBlurb>
    A practitioner's field notebook for AI tools you can run, wire, script, compare, or
    operationally reason about — Claude Code, Codex CLI, Gemini CLI, NotebookLM, Microsoft
    Copilot Studio + Agents Toolkit, GitHub Copilot, OpenClaw, and the MCP servers that wire
    them together. Written by someone learning these in public. Audience is tech practitioners
    catching up on the AI tooling shipping right now — Sush himself plus people like him.
    Junior devs welcome (we explain jargon on first use). Density allowed, marketing voice
    not allowed.
  </SectionBlurb>

  <SectionHead num="0.2" title="Why this exists" />
  <SectionBlurb>
    Most AI-tooling content online is one of: <strong>vendor docs</strong> (exhaustive, dense,
    pitch-shaped), <strong>AI-generated SEO tutorials</strong> (worthless), <strong>vendor
    blogs</strong> (their own pitch, not unbiased), <strong>HN/Reddit threads</strong> (lottery),
    or <strong>hot-take Twitter</strong> (low signal). There's no plain-English, opinionated,
    honest-take, hands-on reference that compares vendor tooling fairly across Anthropic, OpenAI,
    Google, Microsoft, and the open-source side. Claw is that — written by someone learning
    these tools in public, with verification states made visible.
  </SectionBlurb>

  <SectionHead num="0.3" title="Important — Claw is independent" />
  <SectionBlurb>
    Claw is <strong>not operated by Anthropic, OpenAI, Google, Microsoft, or the OpenClaw
    project</strong>. It's a personal volunteer reference. Where official docs and Claw
    disagree, trust the official docs — they're probably newer than this page. We link to them
    on every entry. Disputes welcome via the dispute mechanism (§0.8 below).
  </SectionBlurb>

  <SectionHead num="0.4" title="Verification states (the legend)" verb="every applicable page declares one" />
  <SectionBlurb>
    Each page or field note declares one verification state, shown in the margin column:
    <ul style="margin-top: var(--space-2); padding-left: var(--space-5);">
      <li><strong>SOURCED</strong> — researched from official public docs, repos, or vendor blogs. Sush hasn't personally tested. Starting state for most entries.</li>
      <li><strong>TRIED</strong> — Sush (or a contributor) has run it on a real machine, with date · version · platform · account tier captured.</li>
      <li><strong>VERIFIED</strong> — tried and considered correct (no surprises, no undocumented caveats). The highest signal.</li>
      <li><strong>DISPUTED</strong> — a reader has raised that something is incorrect, with linked discussion.</li>
      <li><strong>PLANNED</strong> — stub. Does NOT appear in top nav until promoted.</li>
    </ul>
    Most entries are <code>sourced</code> on day 1 — Sush prepopulates the learning roadmap from public docs so he knows what's possible to try. As he experiments, entries flip to <code>tried</code> with the actual session log + platform/version. We don't backfill claims we haven't verified.
  </SectionBlurb>

  <SectionHead num="0.5" title="The voice + scope rules" />
  <SectionBlurb>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Plain English.</strong> Forbidden words are enforced in CI: <em>frontier · ecosystem · multimodal · agentic capability · in layman's terms · AI-powered · robust · scalable · holistic · synergies · game changer · mission-critical · moat · differentiator · flagship</em>. <!-- voice-lint:ignore --></li>
      <li><strong>Always explain with examples · scenarios · comparisons.</strong> Definitions alone are not enough.</li>
      <li><strong>Always answer "why does this matter"</strong> for important concepts. If we can't, we leave the section empty rather than padding.</li>
      <li><strong>Honest take.</strong> If a feature is buggy, brittle, or undocumented, the page says so. Field notes carry a dispute link — readers can raise that a note conflicts with their experience, with context.</li>
      <li><strong>Quality over speed.</strong> No marketing voice, no urgency push, no email walls.</li>
      <li><strong>Scope guardrails.</strong> Claw does NOT publish: prompt-engineering articles · model benchmark rankings · AI ethics/regulation commentary · general "what is AI?" explainers · vendor PR reposts · AI news/punditry · customer engagement detail. Those belong on other planets (Plain AI), other surfaces (Earth blog), or nowhere.</li>
      <li><strong>Sush is the primary reader.</strong> The site is for <em>him</em> first, then everyone who finds it useful. That's the order.</li>
    </ul>
  </SectionBlurb>

  <SectionHead num="0.6" title="Who built this" />
  <SectionBlurb>
    Built by <strong>Sush (Susanth Sutheesh)</strong>, Copilot Solution Engineer at Microsoft New
    Zealand. 18+ years in IT — infra admin background, not a developer by training. Still feels
    like the curious intern on every new product. <em>What overflows lands here.</em>
    <br /><br />
    <strong>Microsoft does not sponsor, review, or approve Claw.</strong> This is personal
    volunteer work, written outside work hours, on personal hosting. The takes here are
    independent — not Microsoft's official position. All Microsoft-related content on Claw uses
    only publicly-sourced material (Microsoft Learn, official blogs, public GitHub, Sush's own
    experiments). No customer engagement detail. No internal-only material.
  </SectionBlurb>

  <SectionHead num="0.7" title="Where this sits in the cosmos" verb="7 worlds · own atmospheres · shared belief" />
  <SectionBlurb>
    Claw is one of seven sites in the <strong>A Guide to Cloud</strong> family. Each planet has its
    own atmosphere — own font, palette, voice register, tech stack. The only universal rules across
    the cosmos are <em>quality, value, usability, honesty, don't collide, and a strict firewall
    between free and paid surfaces</em>.
    <ul class="cosmos-map" style="list-style: none; padding-left: 0; margin: var(--space-3) 0; display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: var(--space-2);">
      {cosmosMap.map((p) => (
        <li>
          <strong style="font-family: var(--font-mono);">
            {p.slug === 'earth' ? '🌍' : p.slug === 'guided' ? '🌑' : '🪐'} {p.name}
          </strong>
          {p.here ? (
            <span> — you are here</span>
          ) : (
            <span> — <a href={p.url} rel="noopener">{p.url.replace(/^https?:\/\//, '').replace(/\/$/, '')}</a> — {p.tagline}</span>
          )}
        </li>
      ))}
    </ul>

    <a href="https://cosmos.aguidetocloud.com/" class="cosmos-tour-cta" rel="noopener" aria-label="Open the visual cosmos atlas — every planet on one map">
      <span class="cosmos-tour-cta__marker" aria-hidden="true">[*]</span>
      <span class="cosmos-tour-cta__label">View the whole cosmos atlas</span>
      <span class="cosmos-tour-cta__arrow" aria-hidden="true">→</span>
    </a>

    Read the <a href="https://learn.aguidetocloud.com/reference/cosmos-philosophy/" rel="noopener">cosmos philosophy</a>
    if that frame intrigues you.
  </SectionBlurb>

  <SectionHead num="0.8" title="How to disagree / correct us" />
  <SectionBlurb>
    Each field note has a <strong>dispute link</strong> — click it to raise that a note conflicts
    with your experience, with context. The Bracket Mark logo <code>[*]</code> is the disagree-here
    icon throughout the site — it reads as <em>footnote · annotation · reference · code</em>, which
    is the posture of every page here.
    <br /><br />
    Pull requests welcome at
    <a href="https://github.com/susanthgit/claw-planet">github.com/susanthgit/claw-planet</a>.
    Updates are public, with date and reason.
  </SectionBlurb>
</BaseLayout>
